    "rek_title": "Chromosome arm aneuploidies shape tumour evolution, metastasis, chemotherapy response and patient prognosis",
    "rek_description_xsdmf_id": null,
    "rek_description": "Genomic instability results in the acquisition of mutations and copy number alterations, including chromosome arm aneuploidies (CAAs). CAAs occur in 90% and 55% of all solid and haematological cancers respectively, occurring ~30 times more frequently than expected by size, as well as on average affecting the cancer genome 2.5 times more than mutations and focal copy number changes.Here, we determine and investigate the complete landscape of CAAs that occur across primary and metastatic tumours to understand how CAAs shape drug response, cancer prognosis, metastasis and its interplay with other germline, somatic and molecular hallmarks of cancer.Our analyses provided hitherto unknown insights into the evolution of tumours and open up three exciting new areas of study, including new potential personalised treatments for 17 cancer types.Our most unexpected finding was that chromosome arm gains and losses predict drug response much better than well-established genetic abnormalities, such as mutations. We used artificial intelligence to identify 31 chromosome arm gains or losses that profoundly change the response of cancer cells to 56 different chemotherapeutic drugs. We also uncovered 1,024 potential synthetic lethal pharmacogenomic interactions.Our work also revealed new insights into tumour evolution. Solid tumours usually initially gain chromosome arms and lose multiple arms later during development. Blood cancers, on the other hand, acquire only few chromosome arm abnormalities and show more gains than losses.We found that chromosome arm gains and losses could also predict patient survival outcome in 58 per cent of nearly 7000 patients with 19 types of cancer. Unexpectedly, although chromosome arm gains and losses are abnormal, for 1 in 4 patients they predict better survival outcome.CAAs are associated with both tumour drivers and suppressive hallmarks of cancer development in a cancer type-dependent manner, suggesting that CAAs influence multiple aspects of tumour evolution.We also identify stemness and homologous recombination deficiency - loss of heterogeneity (HRD-LOH) deficiency as the most important molecular determinant of CAA levels in tumours.Our findings further reveal that blood and solid cancers differ profoundly in their CAA landscapes, and that CAAs correlate positively with genomic instability, homologous recombination defects, DNA damage response, chromothripsis, intra-tumour heterogeneity, TP53 and RB1 mutations, mutation burden, neoantigen load, proliferation, virus infection, fibroblast serum response and hypoxia. In contrast, it correlates negatively with germline predisposition, KRAS, VHL, CTCF, ARID1A and PIK3CA mutations, inflammation, immune cell infiltration, angiogenesis and angiogenesis.CAAs and mutations jointly shape malignant disease progression, including directional tumour evolution, but with distinct trajectories in different cancer types. Relative to primary tumours, CAAs are enriched in metastases. We observe distinct patterns of acquisitions of CAAs and single-gene alterations for metastatic dissemination in solid cancers. There is relatively low homogeneity across metastatic sites in four solid cancer types, including breast, prostate, non-small cell lung and colorectal cancers. Interestingly, we identify metastatic site-specific enrichment of specific CAAs and single-gene alterations. Thus, along with single-gene alterations, CAAs also shape cancer metastasis.",
